Here is a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specified word using `std::ifstream`, `std::string`, and `std::getline`. This example assumes the word to search for is "apple". You can modify it to search for any target word by changing the `target` string.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "example.txt";
    std::string target = "apple";
    int count = 0;

    std::ifstream file(filename);
    if (!file.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file: " << filename << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        size_t pos = line.find(target);
        if (pos != std::string::npos) {
            count++;
        }
    }

    file.close();
    std::cout << "The word \"" << target << "\" occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Make sure to replace "example.txt" with the path to your input text file. This program will read the file line by line, search for the target word "apple" in each line using `std::string::find()`, and increment the count if found. Once all lines have been processed, it will display the total count and exit.
